{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489115","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489115"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:05:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:05:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"595"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"595","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/595"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.4,0.05,0.31,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"595"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115073"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"595","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/595"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"595"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97081"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"29"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"88"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"2247"},{"type":"tags","id":"2280"},{"type":"tags","id":"2286"},{"type":"tags","id":"2496"},{"type":"tags","id":"2702"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"930"},{"type":"contributions","id":"953"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10398"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10554"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18061"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35733"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115073","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115073"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 75-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-week history of progressive dyspnoea, right-sided pleuritic chest pain, and a dry cough. She is able to walk 100m before needing to stop and catch her breath. She has a medical history of myocardial infarction two years ago. She has a 30 pack-year smoking history. She takes aspirin and a statin. There is no history of weight loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears mildly unwell. Her pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. On respiratory examination, there is dullness to percussion and crackles in the right lower zone. Chest X-ray reveals right-sided pleural effusion with blunting of the costophrenic angle. Pleural tap reveals:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPleural/serum protein ratio 0.7 (\u0026lt;0.5)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPleural/serum lactate dehydrogenase (LDH) ratio 0.8 (\u0026lt;0.6)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPleural fluid LDH 150 U/L (\u0026lt;200)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Congestive cardiac failure","Pneumonia","Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease","Lung malignancy","Meigs syndrome"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features suggestive of an exudative pleural effusion. Light\u0027s criteria are used to differentiate between transudative and exudative effusions, with an accuracy \u0026gt;90%. An effusion is exudative if it meets any ONE of these criteria:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPleural/serum protein ratio \u0026gt;0.5\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPleural/serum LDH ratio \u0026gt;0.6\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPleural fluid LDH \u0026gt;2/3 upper limit of normal serum LDH\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, both the protein and LDH ratios meet exudative criteria. \u003Cstrong\u003EPneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E with parapneumonic effusion remains the most likely diagnosis despite the absence of significant fever. The presence of pleuritic chest pain, dry cough, crackles on examination, and an exudative effusion are highly suggestive of pneumonia. Elderly patients frequently do not mount a significant febrile response to infection, making this presentation particularly common in this age group.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECongestive cardiac failure\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes a transudative effusion due to increased hydrostatic pressure. The pleural fluid analysis here does not support this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic obstructive pulmonary disease\u003C/strong\u003E does not typically cause pleural effusions unless complicated by infection or heart failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELung malignancy\u003C/strong\u003E, while an important cause of exudative effusions and should be considered in any smoker, typically presents more insidiously over months rather than weeks. While the absence of fever might suggest malignancy, the acute onset of pleuritic pain and relatively short duration of symptoms make infection more likely. Malignant effusions usually present with more constitutional symptoms like weight loss, which is absent here. Additionally, malignant effusions often have higher LDH levels than seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeigs syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E, characterized by the triad of benign ovarian tumour, ascites, and pleural effusion, is unlikely given the acute presentation and absence of pelvic symptoms or ascites.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Light\u0027s criteria help differentiate between transudative and exudative pleural effusions with \u003E90% accuracy","An exudative pleural effusion is diagnosed if any one of Light\u0027s three criteria are met","Pneumonia commonly presents with an exudative pleural effusion and pleuritic chest pain, even without significant fever"],"references":["Light RW, Macgregor MI, Luchsinger PC, Ball WC, Jr. Pleural effusions: the diagnostic separation of transudates and exudates. Ann Intern Med. 1972;77(4):507-13.","Saguil A, Wyrick K, Hallgren J. Diagnostic approach to pleural effusion. Am Fam Physician. 2014;90(2):99-104."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97081"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"595"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97081","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97081"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-22T09:26:30+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-22T09:26:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"595"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115073"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"29","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/29"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2c","name":"Patholog